listenbuddy:
```
..listen, buddy, I don't know who you are or what kind of raiding you do. Me, I'm a mythic raider in a world top 10 guild. I raid 6 days a week, and in a normal week the 7th day is on mmo-champion perfecting my rotation. Yesterday I did 600k sustained dps on Guarm, a new PR for me. Looking at joining the world first race this tier, for the first time since I got RSI a few years back, and I think I can win one, or at least place in the top 5. Not bragging, just establishing who I am and what I'm about. 100 wipes per night is no picnic.
There are two kinds of raiders: Mythic raiders, and everyone else. I don't care what kind of class we're talking about, or which role you play, or how many days or how many raids a week, everyone falls into one of those two categories. The raiders who are not competitors? They'll back off if it's starting to get uncomfortable. Why? Because they have no reason to push themselves that hard. In terms of progress, if they push past normal and into heroic or beyond, they won't stay there for more than a very short amount of time before backing off, because it's uncomfortable for them, and they don't feel the need to go that far.

Mythic raiders? They aren't pushing themselves to the point of it being abject suffering for no good reason, they know that on the other side of that suffering, there are gains. They know that as the tiers go by, they'll be able to go a little harder and do a little more damage because of that suffering, and they know that from those gains, comes getting that much closer to winning races, or that parsing competition, or being rank 1 allstar, or whatever it is that, for them, translates into 'competition'. Usually it's about some parse or another, but it can even mean being the first to the top of that wowprogress page for your server, or just beating your own PR in an archi pug that you do alone every week. There's a challenge, and they feel the need to meet it.```
